# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: iac-security-scanning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Originally written by Michael DeHaan in 2012, and acquired by Red Hat in 2015, Ansible is designed to configure both Unix-like systems and Microsoft Windows.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible is agentless, relying on temporary remote connections via SSH or Windows Remote Management which allows PowerShell execution.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The Ansible control node runs on most Unix-like systems that are able to run Python, including Windows with Windows Subsystem for Linux installed.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] System configuration is defined in part by using its own declarative language.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The term "ansible" was coined by Ursula K.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Le Guin in her 1966 novel *Rocannon's World*, and refers to fictional instantaneous communication systems.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The Ansible tool was developed by Michael DeHaan, the author of the provisioning server application Cobbler and co-author of the Fedora Unified Network Controller (Func) framework for remote administration.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] (originally AnsibleWorks, Inc.) was the company founded in 2013 by DeHaan, Timothy Gerla, and Saïd Ziouani to commercially support and sponsor Ansible.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Red Hat acquired Ansible in October 2015.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible helps to manage multiple machines by selecting portions of Ansible's inventory stored in simple plain text files.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The inventory is configurable, and target machine inventory can be sourced dynamically or from cloud-based sources in different formats (YAML, INI).
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Sensitive data can be stored in encrypted files using Ansible Vault since 2014.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] In contrast with other popular configuration-management software — such as Chef, Puppet, Salt and CFEngine — Ansible uses an *agentless* architecture, with Ansible software not normally running or even installed on the controlled node.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Instead, Ansible orchestrates a node by installing and running *modules* on the node temporarily via SSH.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] For the duration of an orchestration task, a process running the module communicates with the controlling machine with a JSON-based protocol via its standard input and output.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] When Ansible is not managing a node, it does not consume resources on the node because no daemons are run or software installed.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible requires Python to be installed on all managing machines, including pip package manager along with configuration-management software and its dependent packages.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Managed network devices require no extra dependencies and are agentless.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The control node (master host) is intended to manage (orchestrate) target machines (nodes termed as "inventory", see below).
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Control nodes can be run from Linux and Unix-like operating systems (including MacOS); Windows OSs are only supported through the Windows Subsystem for Linux.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible does not require a single controlling machine for orchestration, ensuring that disaster recovery is simple.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Nodes are managed by the controlling node over SSH.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Modules are mostly standalone and can be written in a standard scripting language (such as Python, Perl, Ruby, Bash, etc.).
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] One of the guiding goals of modules is idempotency, which means that even if an operation is repeated multiple times (e.g., upon recovery from an outage), it will always place the system into the same state.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Location of target nodes is specified through inventory configuration lists (INI or YAML formatted) located at `/etc/ansible/hosts` (on Linux).
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The configuration file lists either the IP address or hostname of each node that is accessible by Ansible.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] In addition, nodes can be assigned to groups.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] This configuration file specifies three nodes: the first node is specified by an IP address, and the latter two nodes are specified by hostnames.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Additionally, the latter two nodes are grouped under the `webservers` group.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible can also use a custom *Dynamic Inventory* script, which can dynamically pull data from a different system, and supports groups of groups.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Playbooks are YAML files that store lists of tasks for repeated executions on managed nodes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Each Playbook maps (associates) a group of hosts to a set of roles.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Each role is represented by calls to Ansible tasks.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] The Ansible Automation Platform (AAP) is a REST API, web service, and web-based interface (application) designed to make Ansible more accessible to people with a wide range of IT skillsets.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] It is a platform composed of multiple components including developer tooling, an operations interface, as well as an Automation Mesh to enable automation tasks at scale across data centers.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] AAP is a commercial product supported by Red Hat, Inc. but derived from 17+ upstream open source projects including the AWX upstream project (formerly Ansible Tower), which has been open source since September 2017.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] There also is another open source alternative to Tower, Semaphore, written in Go.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Control machines have to be a Linux/Unix host (for example BSD, CentOS, Debian, macOS, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise, Ubuntu), and Python 2.7 or 3.5 is required.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Managed nodes, if they are Unix-like, must have Python 2.4 or later.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] For managed nodes with Python 2.5 or earlier, the `python-simplejson` package is also required.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Since version 1.7, Ansible can also manage Windows nodes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] In this case, native PowerShell remoting supported by the WS-Management protocol is used instead of SSH.
[src:iac-security-scanning/ansible-software] Ansible can deploy to bare metal hosts, virtual machines, and cloud environments.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM applied over the lifecycle of a system provides visibility and control of its performance, functional, and physical attributes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM verifies that a system performs as intended, and is documented in sufficient detail to support its projected life cycle.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The CM process facilitates orderly management of system information and system changes for purposes such as to revise capability; improve performance, reliability, or maintainability; extend life; reduce costs; reduce risk and liability; or correct defects.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The relatively minimal cost of implementing CM is returned manyfold in cost avoidance.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The lack of CM (or its ineffectual implementation) can be very expensive and sometimes can have such catastrophic consequences such as failure of equipment or loss of life.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM emphasizes the functional relation between parts, subsystems, and systems for effectively controlling system change.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] It helps to verify that proposed changes are systematically considered to minimize adverse effects.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Changes to the system are proposed, evaluated, and implemented using a standardized, systematic approach that ensures consistency, and proposed changes are evaluated in terms of their anticipated impact on the entire system.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM verifies that changes are carried out as specified and that documentation of items and systems reflects their true configuration.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] A complete CM program includes provisions for the storing, tracking, and updating of all system information on a component, subsystem, and system basis.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] A structured CM program ensures that documentation (e.g., requirements, design, test, and acceptance documentation) for items is accurate and consistent with the actual physical design of the item.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] In many cases, without CM, the documentation exists but is not consistent with the item itself.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] For this reason, engineers, contractors, and management are frequently forced to develop documentation reflecting the actual status of the item before they can proceed with a change.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This reverse engineering process is wasteful in terms of human and other resources and can be minimized or eliminated using CM.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration management originated in the United States Department of Defense in the 1950s as a technical management discipline for hardware material items—and it is now a standard practice in virtually every industry.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The CM process became its own technical discipline in the late 1960s when the DoD developed a series of military standards called the "480 series" (i.e., MIL-STD-480, MIL-STD-481 and MIL-STD-483) that were subsequently issued in the 1970s.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This marked the beginning of what has now evolved into the most widely distributed and accepted standard on CM, ANSI–EIA–649–1998.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Many of these functions and models have redefined CM from its traditional holistic approach to technical management.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Some treat CM as being similar to a librarian activity and break out change control or change management as a separate or standalone discipline.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM is the practice of handling changes systematically so that a system maintains its integrity over time.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM implements the policies, procedures, techniques, and tools that manage, evaluate proposed changes, track change status, and maintain an inventory of system and support documents as the system changes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CM programs and plans provide technical and administrative direction to the development and implementation of the procedures, functions, services, tools, processes, and resources required to successfully develop and support a complex system.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] During system development, CM allows program management to track requirements throughout the life-cycle through acceptance and operations and maintenance.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] As changes inevitably occur in the requirements and design, they must be approved and documented, creating an accurate record of the system status.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Ideally the CM process is applied throughout the system life cycle.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Many professionals mix up or get confused with Asset management (AM, see also ISO/IEC 19770), where it inventories the assets on hand.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The key difference between CM and AM is that the former does not manage the financial accounting aspect but the service that the system supports or in other words, that the latter (AM) is trying to realize value from an IT asset.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The CM process for both hardware and software configuration items comprises five distinct disciplines as established in the MIL–HDBK–61A and in ANSI/EIA-649.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Members of an organization interested in applying a standard change-management process will employ these disciplines as policies and procedures for establishing baselines, manage and control change, and monitor and assess the effectiveness and correctness of progress.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The IEEE 12207 process IEEE 12207.2 also has these activities and adds "Release management and delivery".
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration Identification (CI): consists of setting and maintaining baselines, which define the system or subsystem architecture, components, and any developments at any point in time.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] It is the basis by which changes to any part of a system are identified, documented, and later tracked through design, development, testing, and final delivery.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CI incrementally establishes and maintains the definitive current basis for Configuration Status Accounting (CSA) of a system and its configuration items (CIs) throughout their life cycle (development, production, deployment, and operational support) until disposal.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration Control: includes the evaluation of all change-requests and change-proposals, and their subsequent approval or disapproval.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] It covers the process of controlling modifications to the system's design, hardware, firmware, software, and documentation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration Status Accounting: includes the process of recording and reporting configuration item descriptions (e.g., hardware, software, firmware, etc.) and all departures from the baseline during design and production.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] In the event of suspected problems, operators can quickly verify baseline configuration and approved modifications.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration Verification and Audit: an independent review of hardware and software for the purpose of assessing compliance with established performance requirements, commercial and appropriate military standards, and functional, allocated, and product baselines.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration audits verify that the system and subsystem configuration documentation complies with the functional and physical performance characteristics before acceptance into an architectural baseline.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The software configuration management (SCM) process is looked upon by practitioners as the best solution to handling changes in software projects.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] It identifies the functional and physical attributes of software at various points in time, and performs systematic control of changes to the identified attributes for the purpose of maintaining software integrity and traceability throughout the software development life cycle.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The SCM process further defines the need to trace changes, and the ability to verify that the final delivered software has all of the planned enhancements that are supposed to be included in the release.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] It identifies four procedures that must be defined for each software project to ensure that a sound SCM process is implemented.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] These terms and definitions can change somewhat from standard to standard.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] ITIL specifies the use of a configuration management system (CMS) or configuration management database (CMDB) as a means of achieving industry best practices for Configuration Management.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] CMS helps manage a federated collection of CMDBs.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The benefits of a CMS/CMDB includes being able to perform functions like root cause analysis, impact analysis, change management, and current state assessment for future state strategy development.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] For information assurance, CM can be defined as the management of security features and assurances through control of changes made to hardware, software, firmware, documentation, test, test fixtures, and test documentation throughout the life cycle of an information system.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] For example, configuration requirements may be different for a network firewall that functions as part of an organization's Internet boundary versus one that functions as an internal local network firewall.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration management is used to maintain an understanding of the status of complex assets with a view to maintaining the highest level of serviceability for the lowest cost.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Specifically, it aims to ensure that operations are not disrupted due to the asset (or parts of the asset) overrunning limits of planned lifespan or below quality levels.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] In the military, this type of activity is often classed as "mission readiness", and seeks to define which assets are available and for which type of mission; a classic example is whether aircraft on board an aircraft carrier are equipped with bombs for ground support or missiles for defense.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Configuration management can be used to maintain OS configuration files.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Many of these systems utilize Infrastructure as Code to define and maintain configuration.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The Promise theory of configuration maintenance was developed by Mark Burgess, with a practical implementation on present day computer systems in the software CFEngine able to perform real time repair as well as preventive maintenance.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Understanding the "as is" state of an asset and its major components is an essential element in preventive maintenance as used in maintenance, repair, and overhaul and enterprise asset management systems.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Complex assets such as aircraft, ships, industrial machinery etc. depend on many different components being serviceable.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This serviceability is often defined in terms of the amount of usage the component has had since it was new, since fitted, since repaired, the amount of use it has had over its life and several other limiting factors.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Understanding how near the end of their life each of these components is has been a major undertaking involving labor-intensive record keeping until recent developments in software.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Many types of component use electronic sensors to capture data which provides live condition monitoring.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This data is analyzed on board or at a remote location by computer to evaluate its current serviceability and increasingly its likely future state using algorithms which predict potential future failures based on previous examples of failure through field experience and modeling.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This is the basis for "predictive maintenance".
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Availability of accurate and timely data is essential in order for CM to provide operational value and a lack of this can often be a limiting factor.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Capturing and disseminating the operating data to the various support organizations is becoming an industry in itself.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] The consumers of this data have grown more numerous and complex with the growth of programs offered by original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] These are designed to offer operators guaranteed availability and make the picture more complex with the operator managing the asset but the OEM taking on the liability to ensure its serviceability.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] More recently configuration management has been applied to large construction projects which can often be very complex and have a huge number of details and changes that need to be documented.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] Construction agencies such as the Federal Highway Administration have used configuration management for their infrastructure projects.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] There are construction-based configuration management tools that aim to document change orders and RFIs in order to ensure a project stays on schedule and on budget.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] These programs can also store information to aid in the maintenance and modification of the infrastructure when it is completed.
[src:iac-security-scanning/configuration-management] This study yielded results indicating a benefit to using configuration management on projects of this nature.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:iac-security-scanning/devsecops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code-security-cheat-sheet] Infrastructure as code (IaC), also known as software-defined infrastructure, allows the configuration and deployment of infrastructure components faster with consistency by allowing them to be defined as a code and also enables repeatable deployments across environments.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:iac-security-scanning/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Terraform was launched by HashiCorp in 2014.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] HashiCorp launched the Terraform Module Registry in 2017.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] In 2019, the paid version Terraform Enterprise was introduced.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] In September 2021, HashiCorp announced it would be temporarily pausing its review of community-submitted pull requests for Terraform, citing low staffing in its Terraform Core team.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] On August 10, 2023, HashiCorp announced that all products produced by the company would be relicensed under the Business Source License (BUSL), with HashiCorp prohibiting commercial use of the community edition by those who offer "competitive services".
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Terraform was previously free software available under version 2.0 of the Mozilla Public License (MPL).
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Joe Duffy, founder and CEO of Pulumi, criticized the announcement as "disingenuous" and said, "We tried many times to contribute upstream fixes to Terraform providers, but HashiCorp would never accept them.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] In August 2023, due to Terraform's relicensing, the fork OpenTF was created under the MPL.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] OpenTF was later renamed to OpenTofu and place under The Linux Foundation.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Terraform manages external resources (such as public cloud infrastructure, private cloud infrastructure, network appliances, software as a service, and platform as a service) with "providers".
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] HashiCorp maintains an extensive list of official providers, and can also integrate with community-developed providers.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Users can interact with Terraform providers by declaring resources or by calling data sources.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Rather than using imperative commands to provision resources, Terraform uses declarative configuration to describe the desired final state.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Once a user invokes Terraform on a given resource, Terraform will perform CRUD actions on the user's behalf to accomplish the desired state.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] The infrastructure as code can be written as modules, promoting reusability and maintainability.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] Terraform supports a number of cloud infrastructure providers such as Amazon Web Services, Cloudflare, Microsoft Azure, IBM Cloud, Serverspace, Selectel Google Cloud Platform, Linode, DigitalOcean, Oracle Cloud Infrastructure, Yandex.Cloud, VMware vSphere, and OpenStack.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] It can be configured to make use of multiple cloud platforms.
[src:iac-security-scanning/terraform-software] As of 2019, Terraform is used by companies such as Barclays, Capital One, and GM Cruise.
